<font color="#FF0000">RAGE OVER REASON...</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec  8  2:49:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Yes indeed I know exactly what your saying Paul, there where days when all the sniping at us and seeing our friend get hit when something happened to trigger what I call rage replace/overriding reason. It might have been one bullet too close, or seeing just one too many men get hit and suddenly to was too much. Reason was lost in the rage of ‘Not this time bastard’  And suddenly you found yourself doing something very stupid and not giving a damn, or suddenly there was Sir Charles in the open. Caught flat_footed in the open and the rage took over.  First time it happened to me a sniper had us pinned, one round too damn close it hit the top of my helmet which sent it flying off my head… luck but it was the last straw. I spotted him and my first burst knocked him down but didn’t zap him.. But I didn’t care I stood and walked right at him firing as hard as I could.. I save the details of the rest, but rage had replace reason and maybe it way exactly what we had been trained to react to, don’t know for sure. But there where days when the bear got you and ever once in a while the bear got his due…  Funny part was while it was happening I remembered not hearing a single sound, not even my one weapon going off … After it was over I still could not hear the guys yelling at me…. Took a while for this dumb grunt to realize the ringing in my ears was really loud for some reason… <br><br>
Cook, I understand about the fear of not being there for someone,  when I was hit and sent to the 7th field Hosp in Japan when they told me I was going home and not back to my men in ‘Nam.. that fear was realized. Funny thing fear &amp; rage emotions so powerful you never truly realize just how powerful they are till something like that happens to you….<br><br>
Gary 'J.'
